Vheadline
p2
VSumptuous audio-visual treat
p3
sVnews
p4
VThe &#8216;L.V.Memorial Concerts,&#8217; organised by the Rasika Ranjana Sabha, Tiruchi, in memory of its former secretary, L. Venkataraman provided the music lovers  with yet another opportunity to enjoy a variety of  concerts.The nine-day-long programme commenced with a vocal concert by Sowmya Rengarajan. It was followed by  the vocal recital of Seetha Rajan, who runs Bala Brindam Gurukulam in Chennai. She was accompanied by T.H.Vasantha on the violin and S.J. Arjun Ganesh on the mridangam.A  Bharathanatyam performance by Rama Vaidyanathan of New Delhi marked the third day&#8217;s programme. K. Sivakumar did the nattuvangam, with Ramu Ramachandran rendering vocal support and G.S.Rajan and Sumod Sridhar playing the flute and mridangam respectively.T.V.Sankaranayanan presented an enchanting  concert on the fourth  day. The fifth day&#8217;s programme included  a full-length comedy play, &#8216;Galatta Kudumbam,&#8217; directed by Ezhichur Aravindan and presented by Sri Satyasai Creations, Chennai.M. Sowmya and party, Mambalam sisters and Malladi Brothers presented  concerts on  the next three days.  While Mambalam Sisters were accompanied by R. Hemalatha on the violin, Kallidaikurichi K. Sivakumar on the mridangam and K.S.Rangachari on the kanjira. T.V.Ramanujacharulu  (violin), R. Madvaprasad  (mridangam) and H. Paramasivam  (kanjira) lent  support to  Malladi Brothers.Geetha Krishnamurthy&#8217;s  veena concert  on the final day was  soothing.  The recital started with the Nattai kriti,  &#8216;Swaminatha&#8217;. Her rendering of Kalyanavasantham, Ritigowla and Mukhari ragas was  impressive.Geetha&#8217;s main piece, &#8216;Sri Kantimathi&#8217; in Hemavathi  was remarkably brilliant and rendered with bhava.  Her swaraprastharas revealed her strength in laya. Thanam was rendered with high dexterity and competence. Her rendition of Nalinakanti reminded one of her guru, Chittibabu.  The musical feast concluded with a Khamas javali, &#8216;Apaduru&#8217; and a tillana in Dhanasri. She was ably supported by Tirupati M. Sudhakar on the mridangam, who displayed  considerable individuality in the thani, and H. Sivaramakrishnan on the ghatam.
